Here are some examples and explanations of using `async/await` in JavaScript, gathered from the [Modern JavaScript Tutorial](https://javascript.info):

### Fetching and Displaying GitHub Avatar with Async/Await
This example demonstrates fetching user data asynchronously from JSON endpoints to display and then remove a GitHub avatar using `async/await`, improving readability over chained `.then` calls.
```javascript
async function showAvatar() {
  // read our JSON
  let response = await fetch('/article/promise-chaining/user.json');
  let user = await response.json();

  // read GitHub user
  let githubResponse = await fetch(`https://api.github.com/users/${user.name}`);
  let githubUser = await githubResponse.json();

  // show the avatar
  let img = document.createElement('img');
  img.src = githubUser.avatar_url;
  img.className = "promise-avatar-example";
  document.body.append(img);

  // wait 3 seconds
  await new Promise((resolve, reject) => setTimeout(resolve, 3000));

  img.remove();

  return githubUser;
}

showAvatar();
```

### Basic Await Usage in Async Function
Shows how `await` is used within an `async` function to handle promises, pausing function execution until the promise resolves.
```javascript
async function f() {
  let promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve("done!"), 1000)
  });

  let result = await promise; // wait until the promise resolves (*)

  alert(result); // "done!"
}

f();
```

### Rewrite Rethrow Example with Async/Await and Loop
This code snippet shows replacing a recursive Promise-based error handling ('rethrow') with a loop using async/await for better clarity and performance.
```javascript
class HttpError extends Error {
  constructor(response) {
    super(`${response.status} for ${response.url}`);
    this.name = 'HttpError';
    this.response = response;
  }
}

async function loadJson(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  if (response.status === 200) {
    return response.json();
  }
  throw new HttpError(response);
}

async function demoGithubUser() {
  let name;
  while (true) {
    name = prompt("Enter a name?", "iliakan");
    try {
      const user = await loadJson(`https://api.github.com/users/${name}`);
      alert(`Full name: ${user.name}.`);
      return user;
    } catch (err) {
      if (err instanceof HttpError && err.response.status === 404) {
        alert("No such user, please reenter.");
      } else {
        throw err;
      }
    }
  }
}

demoGithubUser();
```

These examples cover basic to advanced usage scenarios of `async/await` in JavaScript, illustrating how to handle asynchronous operations cleanly and effectively.

Here's some documentation and examples on how to use generics in TypeScript:

### Define a Generic Interface in TypeScript
This snippet defines a simple generic interface `I<T>` with a single property `value` of type `T`. This allows for flexible type definitions.

```typescript
interface I<T> {
    value: T;
}
```

### Define Generic TypeScript Interfaces
These examples illustrate creating generic TypeScript interfaces. Generics allow interfaces to maintain type safety across various data types.

```typescript
export interface M<T> { field: T; }
export interface N<U> extends M<U> { other: U; }
```

### Define Generic Comparable Interface and Implementations
This demonstrates defining a generic `Comparable` interface with a `compareTo` method and implementing it in class `A`.

```typescript
interface Comparable<T> {
   compareTo(other: T): number;
}
interface I<T> {
    x: Comparable<T>;
}
interface K<T> {
   x: A<T>;
}
class A<T> implements Comparable<T> { compareTo(other: T) { return 1; } }
```

### Define and Call Generic TypeScript Function
The function `foo<T>` accepts a value of type `T` and two functions, `a` and `b`, showing how type parameters can be inferred.

```typescript
function foo<T>(x: T, a: (x: T) => T, b: (x: T) => T) {
    var r!: (x: T) => T;
    return r;
}

var r1 = foo('', (x: string) => '', (x: Object) => null); // any => any
var r1ii = foo('', (x) => '', (x) => null); // string => string
var r2 = foo('', (x: string) => '', (x: Object) => ''); // string => string
var r3 = foo(null, (x: Object) => '', (x: string) => ''); // Object => Object
var r4 = foo(null, (x) => '', (x) => ''); // any => any
var r5 = foo(new Object(), (x) => '', (x) => ''); // Object => Object

enum E { A }
enum F { A }

var r6 = foo(E.A, (x: number) => E.A, (x: F) => F.A); // number => number
```

### Define Generic Functions for Type Inference
These functions demonstrate TypeScript's type inference capabilities, showcasing how it works with generic parameters.

```typescript
function fun1<T>(x: T, y: T) {
    return randBool() ? x : y;
}

function fun2<T, U>(x: T, y: U) {
    return randBool() ? x : y;
}

function fun3<T>(...args: T[]): T {
    return args[+randBool()];
}
```

These examples cover defining generic interfaces, classes, and functions, as well as utilizing generics for type inference and safe operations across multiple types in TypeScript.

Here is documentation on Node.js file system operations, both promise-based and synchronous:

### Promise-based File System Operations

The `fs/promises` API provides asynchronous file system methods that return promises, perfect for modern async/await patterns while ensuring non-blocking operations:
```javascript
import * as fs from 'node:fs/promises';

try {
  await fs.unlink('/tmp/hello');
  console.log('successfully deleted /tmp/hello');
} catch (error) {
  console.error('there was an error:', error.message);
}
```
- **Characteristics**:
  - Returns promises
  - Non-blocking
  - Compatible with async/await
  - Uses Node.js threadpool

### Synchronous File System Operations

These APIs block the Node.js event loop and JavaScript execution until the operation is complete. Ideal for cases where blocking behavior is acceptable:
```javascript
import * as fs from 'node:fs';

try {
  fs.unlinkSync('/tmp/hello');
  console.log('successfully deleted /tmp/hello');
} catch (err) {
  // handle the error
}
```
- **Characteristics**:
  - Blocks event loop
  - Synchronous execution
  - Exceptions thrown immediately

### Further File System Operations

#### Asynchronous Example Using `fs/promises`:
```javascript
const fsPromises = require('node:fs/promises');

async function fileOperations() {
  try {
    await fsPromises.writeFile('example.txt', 'Hello, Node.js!');
    const content = await fsPromises.readFile('example.txt', 'utf8');
    console.log('File content:', content);

    await fsPromises.appendFile('example.txt', '\nAppended line');
    const stats = await fsPromises.stat('example.txt');
    console.log('File size:', stats.size, 'bytes');
    console.log('Is file:', stats.isFile());

    const files = await fsPromises.readdir('.');
    console.log('Directory contents:', files);

    await fsPromises.copyFile('example.txt', 'example-backup.txt');
    await fsPromises.rename('example-backup.txt', 'backup.txt');
    await fsPromises.unlink('backup.txt');

    await fsPromises.mkdir('new-folder', { recursive: true });
    await fsPromises.rmdir('new-folder');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('File operation failed:', error.message);
  }
}
```

Use these operations for integrating efficient file handling in Node.js applications. For more detailed Node.js file system operation documentation, you can check the [Node.js file system documentation](https://nodejs.org/api/fs.html).

Here is the information about routing in **Next.js**:

### Dynamic Route Parameters
- **Context Parameter**: This provides access to dynamic route parameters through the `params` property. It resolves to an object containing route parameters. Useful for routes with dynamic segments like `[id]` or `[...,slug]`.

#### Example:
```typescript
export async function GET(
  request: Request,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ team: string }> }
) {
  const { team } = await params;
  return Response.json({ team });
}
```

### Dynamic Route Handler
- **GET /items/[slug]**: Processes requests with dynamic slug parameters. Receives the slug value from the URL path and uses it to fetch or process specific item data. 

#### Example:
```typescript
export async function GET(
  request: Request,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ slug: string }> }
) {
  const { slug } = await params; // 'a', 'b', or 'c'
}
```

### Catch All API Route Handler
- Implement a catch-all API route that matches multiple path segments and returns them as an array. Pattern `[...slug]` captures all remaining path segments and passes them as a query parameter array.

#### Example:
```typescript
import type { NextApiRequest, NextApiResponse } from 'next';

export default function handler(req: NextApiRequest, res: NextApiResponse) {
  const { slug } = req.query;
  res.end(`Post: ${slug.join(', ')}`);
}
```

### Handling Dynamic API Routes
- This includes creating endpoints with patterns like `/api/post/{pid}` which capture variable segments in the URL path.

#### Example:
```typescript
export default function handler(req, res) {
  const { pid } = req.query;
  res.end(`Post: ${pid}`);
}
```

These examples illustrate how to set up and manage routing, especially dynamic routing, in Next.js. The framework supports both server-side and client-side rendering with facilities for dynamic and static routing.

Here's a brief overview of CSS Flexbox, including examples and explanations:

### CSS Flexbox Layout with `display: flex`
Flexbox is a layout model in CSS that allows you to arrange items in a one-dimensional space, either in rows or columns. This layout is highly useful for aligning and distributing space within a container.

```css
.header {
  display: flex;
}
```

### Example of a CSS Flexbox Layout
Here's a complete example of a multi-row flexbox layout using `display: flex` and `flex-wrap: wrap`. The sizes and space distribution for the header, footer, sidebar, and main content are controlled using specific `flex` property values.

```css
body {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}
body > * {
  background: #eee;
  padding: 2rem;
  text-align: center;
  border: 5px solid white;
}

.header,
.footer {
  flex: 1 100%;
}
.sidebar {
  flex: 1;
}
.main {
  flex: 2;
}
```

### CSS Flexbox Shorthand Property
The `flex` property in Flexbox is shorthand for `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, and `flex-basis`:

```css
.element { flex: 1 1 100px; }
```

- **flex-grow**: Defines the growth factor of a flex item.
- **flex-shrink**: Defines the shrink factor of a flex item.
- **flex-basis**: Defines the initial size of a flex item before excess space is distributed.

For example: 
- `flex: 1` is equivalent to `flex: 1 0px`, which makes the item flexible, allowing it to take up the remaining space proportionally.

These examples and descriptions give you a solid starting point to work with CSS Flexbox for your layouts. You can explore more on [CSS-Tricks Almanac](https://css-tricks.com/almanac/) for detailed insights.

Here is some documentation and examples about JavaScript Promises:

### Creating a JavaScript Promise with an Executor
To create a new Promise, you use the `Promise` constructor, providing an executor function. This function contains the asynchronous operation and receives `resolve` and `reject` callbacks to signal the outcome.

```javascript
let promise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
  // executor (producing code)
});
```

### JavaScript Promise Chaining with Returning Promises
Promise chaining allows sequential execution of asynchronous operations, with each `.then()` returning a new promise that the next handler will wait for.

```javascript
new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve(1), 1000);
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve(result * 2), 1000);
  });
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => resolve(result * 2), 1000);
  });
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
});
```

### JavaScript Promise Chaining Example
This example illustrates sequential asynchronous task execution using `.then()` to process results and pass them to the next operation.

```javascript
new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  setTimeout(() => resolve(1), 1000);
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
  return result * 2;
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
  return result * 2;
}).then(result => {
  alert(result);
});
```

### JavaScript Promises and Async/Await: Asynchronous Operations
This method demonstrates handling asynchronous operations using `async`/`await`, simplifying chaining and error handling with `.catch`.

```javascript
function loadData(url) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      if (url.startsWith("https://")) {
        resolve({data: "Success", url: url});
      } else {
        reject(new Error("Invalid URL"));
      }
    }, 1000);
  });
}

loadData("https://api.example.com")
  .then(result => {
    console.log(result.data);
    return result.url;
  })
  .then(url => {
    console.log(`Loaded from: ${url}`);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error("Error:", error.message);
  });

async function fetchUserData(userId) {
  try {
    let response = await loadData(`https://api.example.com/users/${userId}`);
    console.log("User data loaded:", response.data);
    return response;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Failed to load user:", error.message);
  }
}

fetchUserData(123).then(data => {
  if (data) {
    console.log("Processing:", data);
  }
});
```

### Promise.all: Parallel Execution and Result Aggregation
`Promise.all` is used for executing multiple promises in parallel, returning a single promise that resolves when all of the input promises resolve.

```javascript
Promise.all([
  new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(() => resolve(1), 3000)),
  new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(() => resolve(2), 2000)),
  new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(() => resolve(3), 1000))
]).then(alert); // Output: 1, 2, 3 when all promises are ready
```

This document explains how to create and use Promises, chain them for sequential operations, and execute multiple promises concurrently using `Promise.all`. These features are critical for managing asynchronous tasks in JavaScript effectively.
